### Test Email Sending
```typescript
// utils/email.test.ts
import { describe, it, expect, vi } from 'vitest';
import { sendEmail } from '@/lib/mail';
import { WelcomeEmail } from '@/emails/welcome';

// Mock the email service
vi.mock('@/lib/mail');

describe('Email Templates', () => {
  it('should send welcome email successfully', async () => {
    const mockSendEmail = vi.mocked(sendEmail);
    mockSendEmail.mockResolvedValue({ id: 'test-email-id' });

    const result = await sendEmail({
      to: 'test@example.com',
      subject: 'Welcome!',
      react: WelcomeEmail({
        name: 'Test User',
        email: 'test@example.com',
      }),
    });

    expect(mockSendEmail).toHaveBeenCalledWith({
      to: 'test@example.com',
      subject: 'Welcome!',
      react: expect.any(Object),
    });

    expect(result).toEqual({ id: 'test-email-id' });
  });
});
```

## Best Practices

### Template Design
- Use responsive design principles
- Test across multiple email clients
- Keep file sizes small for faster loading
- Use web-safe fonts and fallbacks
- Include alt text for images

### Content Guidelines
- Clear and concise subject lines
- Personalized greetings when possible
- Clear call-to-action buttons
- Unsubscribe links for marketing emails
- Consistent branding and styling

### Security Considerations
- Validate email addresses before sending
- Use secure token generation for magic links
- Set appropriate expiration times
- Log email sending for audit trails
- Handle bounces and spam complaints

### Performance Optimization
- Use email template caching
- Implement rate limiting
- Queue emails for batch processing
- Monitor delivery rates and metrics
- Handle failures gracefully with retries

